[This article appears to imply there is at least the suspicion of endotheliotropic herpesvirus (EEHV). However, no definitive cause of death has been released. The necropsy results are still pending.

It is unknown at this time why some calves become ill from EEHV hemorrhagic disease and some calves are exposed to the virus without illness. Suspected factors include variations in calf immunity or viral virulence, with the cause likely being multifactorial. Treatment at this time includes antivirals and supportive care, such as rectal or IV fluids, and IV plasma transfusions. Early detection is key, before there are clinical signs, through weekly blood PCR testing. Early treatment, prior to clinical illness, is currently the only option for helping elephants survive hemorrhagic disease. A vaccine, if developed, would decrease severity of disease, but would not prevent transmission (extracted from ProMED-mail 20181207.6192539).

This calf was only 3 days old and may or may not have had a blood test looking for EEHV. Likely this will be in the report when more is known. - Mod.TG

